**Source of truth:** `agent/skills/openquok-core/SKILL.md` — installable OpenClaw skill (`openquok-core`): hard rules, auth, media, workflows, and links. Edit that file when changing what agents should do with the CLI; keep this rule file for Cursor-only best practices.

## Skill layout

- **`SKILL.md`** — Hard rules, auth, core workflow, patterns, gotchas, quick reference. Keep it focused; link out instead of duplicating long examples.
- **`resources/*.md`** — Deeper material agents can load on demand:
  - `command-reference.md` — CLI commands, flags, env vars (not `agent/README.md`; skill install path has no sibling README).
  - `patterns.md` — extended workflows (campaign JSON, batching, retries).
  - `threads-examples.md`, `instagram-standalone-examples.md`, `instagram-business-examples.md` — platform-specific `posts:create` / integration examples.
  - `threads-publish.md` — server publish behavior summarized in markdown (never link to `.ts` / backend paths from the skill).
- **`SKILL.md` tone** — imperative, short tables and bullets; no tutorial prose; shell-safety rules for untrusted input; defer command lists and long bash to `resources/`.
- **Links:** Only reference markdown under this skill directory (or stable external URLs in the front matter). Do not link to monorepo source files (TypeScript, tests, etc.) from skill content; summarize behavior in a new `resources/*.md` file instead.

## Best practices

- **Be concise** — instruct the model on what to do, not how to be an AI.
- **Safety first** — if your skill uses exec, ensure prompts don't allow arbitrary command injection from untrusted input.
